The paper discusses a privacy-preserving technique for deep learning based on data morphing, which suggests that it could belong to the categories of computer security (cs.CR), machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision (cs.CV), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper specifically addresses the concern of potential privacy violation in deep learning applications, which aligns with the focus of the cs.CR category. The proposed technique involves morphing data to preserve privacy, which is a key aspect of machine learning and computer vision. The paper also discusses the computational and data transmission overhead, which relates to the cs.DS category. Overall, the paper could fit into multiple categories, but the most likely ones are cs.CR, cs.LG, cs.CV, cs.AI, and cs.DS.
